english:
  title: The Waystation of the High Plain
  author: Kim Geuk-gi
  language: eng
  text: |-
    A hundred years of fleeting life—already fifty springs have passed.
    On this strange and difficult path of the world, few passages lead through.
    Three years away from the capital—what have I accomplished?
    Returning home across ten thousand miles, I bring only this worn body.

    Forest birds, moved by feeling, cry out as they see the traveler.
    Wild flowers, speaking no words, smile and beckon me to linger.

    The demon of poetry strikes from every direction, tormenting me relentlessly.
    Even without the weight of poverty and sorrow, affliction already weighs upon my heart.
  footnotes:
    - The 'demon of poetry' (詩魔) refers to the irresistible compulsion to compose verse, a common conceit in East Asian poetry that suggests inspiration as both blessing and burden.
    - The geographical imagery—three years away from the capital, a journey of ten thousand miles—suggests the poet's exile or extended absence from court, a common experience among Korean literati of the period.
